    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey, i'm looking at my student loan amortization schedule and i'm kinda confused. i've been making my monthly payments on time every month but the principal balance is barely even going down. can you explain how the interest actually gets calculated each month? like, why does it feel like so much of my money is just disappearing instead of hitting the actual loan amount?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Your monthly payment is split between interest and principal, meaning you pay interest on the remaining balance before any part of your payment actually reduces it. Since interest rates are usually fixed, the initial portion of your payment goes almost entirely toward this interest, which is why your principal balance drops so slowly in the early years. Once your balance decreases, less interest is charged each month, allowing more of your payment to finally chip away at the principal.",
